      <h2>Future Worlds: Designing for a Changing Environment</h2>
      <p>Date: <b class='names'>26 June 2021</b></p>
      <p>Time: <b class='names'>3:00 pm – 4:00 pm BST</b></p>
      <p>Location: <b class='names'><a href="https://rye.sussexwildlifetrust.org.uk/discovery-centre" target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer">Rye Harbour Discovery Centre</a>, Harbour Rd, Rye, East Sussex, TN31 7FW</b>
      </p>
      <details>
        <summary>To mark the launch of Joseph William's site-responsive temporary installation at Rye Harbour Nature
          Reserve, join us for a panel debate exploring alternative ecological approaches for designing our future built
          environments, beyond mainstream notions of sustainability.</summary>
        <div class="image">
          <img src="f-w.jpeg" alt="Drawing of antenna on a blue background.">
        </div>
        <p>A multidisciplinary panel of experts including Barry Wark (Director of Biophile and Lecturer at Bartlett
          School of Architecture), Hanif Kara (Director and Co-Founder of AKT II, and Professor at Harvard GSD), and
          moderated by Gonzalo Herrero Delicado (Curator and Lecturer at Central Saint Martins), will examine how we can
          respond through design research to a rapidly changing world and the current climatic emergency. More Speakers
          to be announced soon</p>
        <p>Places are limited - <a
            href="https://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/future-worlds-designing-for-a-changing-environment-tickets-157542366459"
            target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">register now</a></p>
      </details>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h2>Cloudscape Textile Printing with Sarah Desmarais</h2>
      <p>Dates: <b class='names'>2 June 2021</b></p>
      <p>Time: <b class='names'>10:00 am – 4:00 pm BST</b></p>
      <p>Location: <b class='names'><a href="https://ryecreativecentre.co.uk/plan-your-visit" target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer">Rye Creative Centre</a>, New Rd, Rye TN31 7LS</b>
      </p>
      <details>
        <summary>Climate Art invites you to join a free drop-in workshop led by Sarah Desmarais – a designer-maker and
          researcher working with slow, sustainable print processes.
          You’ll have the opportunity to try out a centuries-old Japanese resist-printing technique involving stencil
          cutting, printing with a rice paste resist, and indigo dyeing. This slow print process offers a rare
          opportunity to rethink our relationship with fast fashion and the environmental repercussions of textile
          production while reconnecting with the natural world.</summary>
        <p>The workshop will be organised in a covid-secure way, out of doors or in a well-ventilated indoor space.
          Suitable for all age groups (children must be supervised).
          All materials will be provided free of charge.</p>
        <h3>About Sarah Desmarais</h3>
        <p>The recipient of a 2019 Queen Elizabeth Scholarship Trust award, Sarah Desmarais has recently undertaken
          artist residencies with Bow Arts and the Museum of Domestic Design and Architecture. She also supervises
          postgraduate research at the Royal College of Art.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
